<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <meta name="theme-color" content="#455b5a" />
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="Lyrium — a quiet place for lyrics and ideas. Your words stay yours."
    />
    <title>Lyrium</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles.css" />
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="shell">
      <main class="site-main landing-main">
        <div class="notebook-sheet">
          <article class="manifesto" aria-labelledby="letter-heading">
            <header class="manifesto-head">
              <h1 id="letter-heading" class="manifesto-title">AI can’t write lyrics</h1>
            </header>
            <div class="manifesto-body">
              <p>
                Two hundred songwriting apps don’t get this. AI just writes the song, and the output
                is derivative by design. Great art is a product of emotion and experience by the
                unconscious mind, not a rehash of stolen lyrics spewed by matrix math in a data center
                on plowed-over farmland. Expediting the process while undermining the authenticity is
                futile.
              </p>
              <p>
                Lyrium is fundamentally different. It’s built from the ground up to cultivate
                connections and inspiration by tapping a plethora of sources. A rhyme dictionary,
                Roget’s Thesaurus, your sense memories, your journal, and language models tied together
                in a first-of-its-kind interface that exposes the power and flexibility you’d expect
                from a pro app.
              </p>
              <p>
                Tom Petty wrote an entire album looking at magnet words on a music stand. We put a
                galaxy of magnet words right around your notepad that are seeded by your own creative
                process and enhanced by AI. We put the best techniques used by pro songwriters like
                rhyme worksheets and object writing into a deeply interconnected creative process that
                takes you all the way from collecting inspiration, to writing your first line, to
                tracking your final lyrics. <strong>Try it today.</strong>
              </p>
            </div>
          </article>

          <section class="download-section" aria-labelledby="app-store-brand">
            <h2 id="app-store-brand" class="app-download-name" aria-label="Lyrium">lyrium</h2>
            <a
              class="app-store-link"
              href="https://apps.apple.com/us/search?term=Lyrium"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
              aria-label="Download Lyrium on the App Store"
            >
              <img
                src="https://tools.applemediaservices.com/api/badges/download-on-the-app-store/white/en-us?size=250x83"
                alt="Download on the App Store"
                width="250"
                height="83"
                decoding="async"
              />
            </a>
          </section>
        </div>
      </main>

      <footer class="site-footer">
        <nav aria-label="Legal and site">
          <ul class="site-footer-nav">
            <li><a href="/" aria-current="page">Home</a></li>
            <li><a href="/terms.html">Terms</a></li>
            <li><a href="/privacy.html">Privacy</a></li>
            <li><a href="/support.html">Support</a></li>
          </ul>
        </nav>
      </footer>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
